# LeanScene steering rules (starter) — rename to .cursorrules in your project.
#
# Steers an AI agent in a large Unreal Engine 5 scene toward token-efficient
# queries instead of dumping the whole scene. Tune task names to your project.

PRIME RULE
Never pull the whole scene when a narrow query answers the question. Large
outliner / actor list / asset registry dumps blow up the context window and
degrade accuracy. Prefer the lean LeanScene tools below; each returns a fixed,
minimal payload and reports its own per-call token saving.

NEVER DO THESE (the firehose)
- Do not dump the full outliner or read the entire actor list to find or count
  actors.
- Do not fetch a full, verbose actor description when you only need key fields.
- Do not dump the full asset registry to find a handful of offending assets.
- Do not take a screenshot / vision check to confirm what a cheap deterministic
  check can confirm.

USE THE LEAN TOOL FOR THE TASK
- find / inspect actors near a point -> get_actors_in_radius (not the full actor list / outliner)
- understand the level's structure   -> summarize_level (not an outliner dump)
- read one actor's key fields         -> get_actor_brief (not the verbose native "describe actor")
- find unlinked materials             -> get_unlinked_materials (not the whole asset registry)
- find assets missing LODs            -> get_assets_missing_lods (not the whole asset registry)

VERIFY BEFORE VISION
Before any screenshot or vision check, confirm placement with the cheap exact
checks; only fall back to vision if these cannot answer the question:
- verify_bounds    -> is an actor's bounding box what you expect?
- verify_overlap   -> do two actors overlap?
- verify_transform -> is an actor at the expected location?

NOTE
This biases tool selection through descriptions and these rules only. It does not
modify or remove the engine's native tools; simply prefer the lean ones above.
